by bicycle (you often have company from bees, goats and stray dogs along the way because Zambia is an open country). Getting to the local bar (almost everyone here is a drinker, including me, hush hush! It really relaxes the tension) is quite a bit shorter than the 1km grocery store walk does however because Bwambara village is on a hill. The local bar is right at the top of the hill so if you walk straight up from the police station it takes 2.5 minutes. Along the way, you cover 800m and for bonus points, you drop 200m. 200m down in altitude alleviates some of the town's intensity. Along the way (if you are paying attention) you get a taste of the river (one of Bwambara's only streets) and one of the more inhospitable stretches along the route. Along the way to town, I joined the Bwambara police along my way, who were on a half-drunk patrol of the area as they usually are each night. As I approached Bwambara, I passed a local drunk, to my immediate right his saddle was treading knots into the dirt road having been chomped down by oxen as a donkey cart carried the body of a dead chicken.
